<link href="adcp.css" rel="stylesheet"><entry><xh5>lose one’s way • lose way</xh5><p> <i>lose one’s way—</i>1. cease to follow the right track; become lost: The children <u>lost their way</u> in the dark and did no reach home. 2. be unable to find the right road in life: You seem to me like one who has <u>lost his way</u> and made a great error in life.</p><p> <div class="note">Note</div> The expression is not antonymous in meaning to the phrase <b>win one’s way</b>—<i>succeed in following one’s course despite obstacles: </i>The young fellow who will devote himself to agriculture may do even better than the youth who <u>wins his way</u> to the black-coated servitude of a bank.</p><p> <i>lose way</i>—(Nautical) lose speed: The wind failed and dropped to nothing, the dinghy <u>lost way</u> and drifted towards three lighters moored abreast.</p> </entry>
